    tool_output=ToolOutput(
        output='Based on the provided 10-K filing for United States Steel Corporation for the fiscal year ended December 31, 2024, here are the specific extracts for your four requests:\n\n### 1. Specific Language About What Would Happen if the Merger Fails\n\nThe primary language about the consequences of the merger failing is found in **Item 1A. Risk Factors**, specifically on **page 24** under the heading *"Failure to complete the Merger on a timely basis, or at all, would negatively impact our business and financial condition, as well as the price of our common stock."*\n\nThe filing states that if the Merger is not completed, the ongoing business may be adversely affected as follows:\n> “(i) we may experience negative reactions from the financial markets, including negative impacts on the market price of our common stock; (ii) some of management’s attention will have been directed to the Merger instead of being directed to our own operations and the pursuit of other opportunities that could have been beneficial to us; (iii) the manner in which customers, suppliers and other third parties perceive us may be negatively impacted, which in turn could affect our ability to compete for business; (iv) we may experience negative reactions from employees and there may be further negative impact on the relationship with the leadership of the USW; (v) we will have expended time and resources that could otherwise have been spent on our business; and (vi) we will not obtain the benefits of NSC’s commitments to the Company, including the commitments to invest at least $2.7 billion of capital and to share technology to protect and grow the Company.”\n\nIt further notes that if the Merger fails, the Company will not realize the stock price premium benefit ($55.00 per share vs. the unaffected price of $22.72) and will have incurred substantial transaction-related fees.\n\n### 2. Discussion of the $2.7 Billion Investment Commitment from Nippon Steel\n\nThere is **no separate, detailed discussion** of the specific terms or earmarking of the $2.7 billion investment commitment within the 10-K text. It is mentioned in passing as a benefit that would be lost if the merger fails.\n\nThe specific mention is in **Item 1A. Risk Factors** on **page 24**, where the Company states:\n> “we will not obtain the benefits of NSC’s commitments to the Company, including the commitments to invest at least $2.7 billion of capital and to share technology to protect and grow the Company.”\n\n### 3. Details About the Merger Agreement Terms and Restrictions on U.S. Steel\'s Business Operations\n\nThe restrictions on U.S. Steel\'s business operations are discussed in **Item 1A. Risk Factors** on **page 24** under the heading *"We are subject to business uncertainties and contractual restrictions while the Merger is pending, which could adversely affect our business."*\n\n> “The Merger Agreement requires us to operate in the ordinary course of business and restricts us, without the consent of Purchaser, from taking certain specified actions agreed by the parties to be outside the ordinary course of business until the pending Merger occurs or the Merger Agreement terminates. These restrictions may prevent us from pursuing otherwise attractive business opportunities and making other changes to our business before completion of the Merger or, if the Merger is not terminated, termination of the Merger Agreement.”\n\nSpecific examples of restricted activities mentioned elsewhere in the document include:\n- **Share Repurchases:** **Page 12, 58:** “The Merger Agreement contains a customary prohibition on U. S. Steel’s ability to engage in additional share repurchases without the consent of Purchaser.”\n- **Debt Incurrence:** **Page 12:** “The Merger Agreement contains customary limitations on U. S. Steel’s ability to incur additional indebtedness without the consent of Purchaser.”\n- **Strategic Transactions:** **Page 12:** “The Merger Agreement contains customary limitations on U. S. Steel’s ability to... [pursue] various possibilities, including exiting lines of business and the sale of certain assets... without the consent of Purchaser.”\n\n### 4. Risk Factors Specifically Related to the Merger\n\nThe specific risks related to the Merger are detailed in **Item 1A. Risk Factors** on **pages 23-25**. The key sub-headings are:\n\n1.  **Failure to complete the Merger on a timely basis, or at all, would negatively impact our business and financial condition, as well as the price of our common stock.**\n    - Discusses the risk of non-completion, including the President\'s order blocking the deal and the subsequent lawsuits.\n    - Details the negative consequences of failure (see point 1 above).\n\n2.  **Expenses related to the pending Merger are significant and will adversely affect our operating results.**\n    - “We have incurred and expect to continue to incur significant expenses in connection with the pending Merger, including legal and investment banking fees and fees incurred in connection with the Merger-related litigation.”\n\n3.  **We are subject to business uncertainties and contractual restrictions while the Merger is pending, which could adversely affect our business.**\n    - Discusses the "ordinary course" covenant and restrictions on business activities (see point 3 above).\n\n4.  **Litigation and union grievances and disputes could result in substantial costs or other negative impacts on the Company.**\n    - “we (along with our directors and officers) may face lawsuits, disputes and/or other actions”\n    - Notes the risk of injunctions preventing the merger.\n\n5.  **The announcement and pendency of the Merger may adversely affect our business, financial condition and results of operations.**\n    - Discusses risks to customer, supplier, and employee relationships.\n    - “Uncertainty about the effect of the Merger on our employees may have an adverse effect on our business... Employee retention may be particularly challenging during the pendency of the Merger.”\n\n6.  **The Merger Agreement contains provisions that eliminate our ability to consider alternative transaction proposals.**\n    - “The Merger Agreement contains non-solicitation provisions that... restrict our ability to solicit, initiate, or knowingly encourage or induce competing third-party proposals”',
